1

00:00:01,800  -->  00:00:05,275
Hopefully, you're starting to feel more comfortable

2

00:00:05,275  -->  00:00:08,830
identifying hypotheses and the types of errors that you can make.

3

00:00:08,830  -->  00:00:13,775
In this video, we'll go through one more example to iterate on these ideas.

4

00:00:13,775  -->  00:00:16,375
This example is one that really helped me connect

5

00:00:16,375  -->  00:00:20,199
all the dots of hypotheses testing and type I and type II errors.

6

00:00:20,199  -->  00:00:22,265
I hope it does the same for you.

7

00:00:22,265  -->  00:00:24,160
Imagine you own a skydiving shop.

8

00:00:24,160  -->  00:00:25,750
And as a part of your job,

9

00:00:25,750  -->  00:00:28,954
you must check parachutes to assure they worked correctly.

10

00:00:28,954  -->  00:00:31,038
There are two potential outcomes,

11

00:00:31,039  -->  00:00:33,945
either a parachute works or it doesn't.

12

00:00:33,945  -->  00:00:37,545
You can create these as our two potential hypotheses.

13

00:00:37,545  -->  00:00:43,359
You know that there are four potential outcomes for each skydiver-parachute combination.

14

00:00:43,359  -->  00:00:47,659
First, you check each parachute to make a decision.

15

00:00:47,659  -->  00:00:51,009
Either the parachute works or it doesn't.

16

00:00:51,009  -->  00:00:52,614
If you determine that it works,

17

00:00:52,615  -->  00:00:55,690
you put it on the shelf for skydivers to use.

18

00:00:55,689  -->  00:00:58,129
If it doesn't, you throw it out.

19

00:00:58,130  -->  00:01:00,913
Now, there are two possible truths,

20

00:01:00,912  -->  00:01:04,569
either the parachute actually works or it doesn't.

21

00:01:04,569  -->  00:01:07,494
For the parachute that we threw out, if it doesn't work,

22

00:01:07,495  -->  00:01:09,594
that's great, but if it did,

23

00:01:09,594  -->  00:01:12,155
then we probably lost like 30 bucks.

24

00:01:12,155  -->  00:01:15,236
Now, for the parachute we put on the shelf,

25

00:01:15,236  -->  00:01:17,649
if it works, then the skydiver uses it

26

00:01:17,650  -->  00:01:20,795
to jump out of a plane and land safely on the ground.

27

00:01:20,795  -->  00:01:22,379
However, if it doesn't,

28

00:01:22,379  -->  00:01:25,909
we clearly just committed the worst type of error possible.

29

00:01:25,909  -->  00:01:28,854
This should clearly be the type I error in this example.

30

00:01:28,855  -->  00:01:32,090
So, the other type of error is the type II error.

31

00:01:32,090  -->  00:01:36,359
This helps us align our null and alternative hypotheses to look like this.

32

00:01:36,359  -->  00:01:38,769
As we know that type I error rate should be

33

00:01:38,769  -->  00:01:41,869
choosing the alternative when the null is true.

34

00:01:41,870  -->  00:01:45,189
And it helps us align an appropriate type I error rate as

35

00:01:45,189  -->  00:01:48,685
one or five percent as entirely too high.

36

00:01:48,685  -->  00:01:51,909
Committing five or even one of these errors out

37

00:01:51,909  -->  00:01:56,000
of every 100 individuals would just be unacceptable.
